projectInfo.name: Site Mapping MaiAini- Ethiopia
projectInfo.shortDescription:
The UN Refugee Agency (UNHCR) is assisting the Ethiopian government in facing the challenges associated with this influx of refugees. Among other things, the UNHCR manages the establishment of refugee settlements, ensures access to basic facilities and provides humanitarian aid.
UNHCR has requested the assistance of CartONG and its community of volunteers to map several camps along the border that do not yet appear on any map. This involves mapping houses/shelters and roads.
projectInfo.description: Ethiopia is one of the largest countries of asylum for refugees of the world and the second largest in Africa, reflecting the fragility and ongoing conflicts in the region. Among the main factors contributing to this situation are the conflicts in South Sudan, the prevailing political environment in Eritrea, and the conflict and drought in Somalia. As of 2017, Ethiopia offers protection to more than 850,000 refugees - the majority of who come from neighbourhood countries. Most are hosted in 27 refugee settlements, where services and opportunities are limited and mainly dependent on humanitarian assistance. The influx of refugees continues, with over 35,000 people coming to seek security and protection within the country's borders over the past year. The UN Refugee Agency (UNHCR) is assisting the Ethiopian government in facing the challenges associated with this influx of refugees. Among other things, UNHCR manages the establishment of settlements, ensures access to basic facilities and provides humanitarian aid. This year, a site planning team is in charge of planning the extension of existing camps in northern Ethiopia. The team lacks maps to better understand the current situation and identify the location of future extensions that are both in a safe areas and sufficiently close to the existing facilities of the former camps and villages of the host communities. UNHCR has requested the assistance of CartONG and its community of volunteers to map these camps, which do not yet appear on any map. This involves mapping houses/shelters and roads. *Watch Philipp's video, UNHCR's site planner, he explains how he will use the map in the field* **HERE**
projectInfo.instructions:
1. Imagery ============ Through the MapGive project, the Humanitarian Information Unit (HIU) of the U.S. Department of State is providing the OpenStreetMap community access to updated satellite imagery services to help assist with humanitarian mapping. This imagery is from DigitalGlobe’s WorldView-01 satellite, and is made up of images taken on May 3, 2018. The images are orthorectified for terrain corrected geographic precision. Additionally, the images have been contrast stretched using a custom stretch in QGIS and processed into a Tiled Map Service (TMS) for increased web performance. --- 2. Buildings ============ * **Be as precise as possible!** _Zoom to distinguish the buildings. Draw the building in its entirety even if it could be partially covered by trees._ ##**How?** *With ID Editor :* 1. Use the tool **area** to draw the buildings 2. Once it's drawn, open the menu on the left of your page and click on the "Building Features" category, then select **"buildings"** (this is the most generic building type, we do not know a more detailed building use because we are just using satellite imagery) 3. Finally, correct the angles and square your buildings by pressing down on the **"S"** key ![how to map a building] (http://cartong.org/sites/cartong/files/GIF_Building_v2.gif) *With editor JOSM:* 1. Use **Draw nodes** tool to draw the buildings, or the **buildings_tools** plug-in 2. Then draw the buildings and add the **building=yes** tag 3. Then, if you use the "draw nodes" tool, think to correct the angles and square the building by pressing **"Q"** key. `Warning: many buildings are very close to each other but do not touch each other. Try to draw them close to each other without connecting or sharing nodes between other buildings, roads or residential/natural areas. In ID Editor, you can avoid having nodes stick to each other by pressing the "Alt" key.` --- 3. Roads network ============ * **Please draw roads that are clearly visible** * **Connect the roads to the existing network** as much as possible. * **Avoid mapping very short roads that do not go anywhere** * **While drawing a road, you may cross your boundary square by a bit** in order to let the person who will draw the square next to yours connect his roads to the existing network. `The classification of roads in Africa is different from Western countries. How roads appear in African countries are not always representative of their economic and social role. In OSM, the typology of roads is based on the importance of roads and not on the type of surface material or their visual appearance. The road classifications proposed in OSM for African countries is based on the mapping experiences of many of these countries, as well as many conversations and discussions, it is more adapted to the context of this continent. ` ##**For this project, we will use the following categories :** **Minor/unclassified road (unclassified) :** For roads on which a 4-wheeled vehicle could pass and connect small villages or hamlet. **Path :** For small roads on which a 4-wheeled vehicle could not pass, but can be used by people on foot or on a two-wheeled vehicle. These roads can connect either uninhabited places or lead to cultivated fields. Only trace major roads that connect to populated places or other roads. **Track :** For smaller roads that are generally used for agricultural or forestry purposes. ##**How ?** *With ID Editor :* 1. Use the **line** tool to draw the roads 2. Once you have drawn a road, go to the menu on the left, find the category that corresponds to the classification of the road or the path (see definition above) *With JOSM:* 1. Use the **Draw nodes** tool to draw roads and paths 2. Draw the road and add the tag corresponding to its classification. **Highway=Unclassified** or **Highway=path** or **Highway=track** (cf. definition above) --- **The mapping you do makes a real difference**: each of your contributions will not only be used by the organization that requested the project, but will also remain permanently in the OSM database and visible and reusable by all. Be as accurate as possible! **Quality is more important than quantity!** Remember that mapping requires patience, attention and care.

**If you have questions, please ask in the comment section, one of our validators will be happy to answer!**
